ce:section.ce:para:
The electrochemical behavior of RF was analyzed at bare SPCE, N-CQD/SPCE, SnO2/SPCE, and N-CQD/SnO2/SPCE by performing distinct CV in 0.1 M PBS (pH 7.0) with the presence of 25 μM RF at the scan rate of 50 mV s−1 are shown in Fig. 4
                        a. The electrochemical response of RF at bare SPCE resulted in a minor oxidation peak at −0.37 V and reduction peak at −0.41 V. On compared to the bare SPCE, N-CQD modified SPCE shows improved redox peaks, indicating the good electrical property of the N-CQD; while the observed slight increased anodic peak at SnO2/SPCE than the N-CQD/SPCE, suggesting that the SnO2 could effectively catalyze the oxidation of RF. Interestingly, N-CQD/SnO2/SPCE exhibited the highest sharp anodic peak at −0.35 V with a high current (19.4 μA) response and the cathodic peak at −0.39 V. From the comparison of CVs of different modified electrodes, it is concluded that the N-CQD/SnO2/SPCE shows meaningfully enhanced redox peak current and its redox peak potential also shifted towards positive. It is also observed that the peak to peak separation (ΔEp
                        ) of the N-CQD/SnO2 modified SPCE is lower (40 mV) than the undoped SnO2 (45 mV) and bare SPCE (61 mV). Thus, the obtained results readily revealed that the electrochemical behavior of RF at the N-CQD/SnO2/SPCE was greatly improved, probably due to the catalytic effect of SnO2 and the synergetic effect of N-CQD in the N-CQD/SnO2 nanocomposite.
